    dcterms:abstract _:n3-7;
    dcterms:title "Christopher Alexander - Sala House";
    paradicms:institution <urn:markdown:Bildungsroman:institution:default>;
    dcterms:creator <urn:markdown:Bildungsroman:person:Christopher%20Alexander>;
    dcterms:relation <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sala_House>, <http://www.wikidata.org/entity/Q18753095>;
    paradicms:collection <urn:markdown:Bildungsroman:collection:default>.
_:n3-7 a paradicms:Text;
    dcterms:creator "Christopher Alexander";
    dcterms:rights <http://rightsstatements.org/vocab/InC/1.0/>;
    dcterms:bibliographicCitation "Alexander, Christopher (1979). The Timeless Way of Building. Oxford University Press. ISBN 978-0-19-502402-9.";
    rdf:value "<blockquote>\n<p>There is one timeless way of building. It is a thousand years old, and the same today as it has ever been. The great traditional buildings of the past, the villages and tents and temples in which man feels at home, have always been made by people who were very close to the center of this way. It is not possible to make great buildings, or great towns, beautiful places, places where you feel yourself, places where you feel alive, except by following this way. And, as you will see, this way will lead anyone who looks for it to buildings which are themselves as ancient in their form, as the trees and hills, and as our faces are.</p>\n</blockquote><p>Christopher Alexander, <em>The Timeless Way of Building</em></p>"
}
<urn:paradicms_etl:pipeline:Bildungsroman:model:45d0eb01baab463d44f481c436316c565dd6f9bc5d92d14fe9058902eab899be> {
<urn:markdown:Bildungsroman:work:Leonardo%20da%20Vinci%20-%20Vitruvian%20man> a paradicms:Work;
    dcterms:abstract _:n3-8;
    dcterms:title "Leonardo da Vinci - Vitruvian man";
    paradicms:institution <urn:markdown:Bildungsroman:institution:default>;
    dcterms:creator <urn:markdown:Bildungsroman:person:Leonardo%20da%20Vinci>;
    paradicms:collection <urn:markdown:Bildungsroman:collection:default>.
_:n3-8 a paradicms:Text;
    dcterms:creator "Steve Jobs";
    rdf:value "<blockquote>\n<p>The doers are the major thinkers. The people that really create the things that change ... are both the thinker doer in one person. If we really go back and examine ... Did Leonardo have a guy off to the side that was thinking five years out in the future what he would paint or the technology he would use to paint? Of course not. Leonardo was the artist but he also mixed all his own paints. He also was a fairly good chemist, knew about pigments, knew about human anatomy, and combining all of those skills together, the art and the science, the thinking and the doing, was what resulted in the exceptional result.</p>\n</blockquote><p>Steve Jobs, interview for the WGBH/BBC series <em>The Machine That Changed The World</em> (1990)</p>"
}
